Am sorry for not mentioning Code queen but I have just edited the story.  You need to stand your ground and connect with the right people.  "The father of my kids gave me two options: ‚Äòyou either choose to quit your job, sit home & take care of the kids or you move out.‚Äô But choosing my career was much better because the relationship was already toxic with a lot of abuse. We did not live together for the 7 years as he worked in the UK. He would come home for 3 weeks a year & would either leave me pregnant or breastfeeding. It was so difficult for me to manage considering I was staying alone with the kids". Atim Joyce Sandra is a single mother of 3 daughters who came to Code Queen to learn how to code, after spending 7 years as a stay home mom. Before being a mom, she had worked as a Computer Lab Technician for 5 years (2009 - 2014) at the College of Computing at Makerere University. Coding had always been her passion, she says, but she didn‚Äôt know where to start until Code Queen/Refactory gave her a chance to pursue her dream. Her journey wasn‚Äôt without challenges. Miss SONAL KADCHHA paid her Refactory Catalyst in 2019 & was selected for a 6-month Bootcamp, she worked on a project with Titl /TrueSoil.  But mid-way into it, the father of her kids returned. He kicked her out and banned her from seeing her kids. She needed to take her kids but she had nowhere to go. That very month he left for the UK, leaving her kids with her in-laws. That‚Äôs when the COVID 19 pandemic started. She begged and bargained with him to allow her to see her kids with no success. She went to different police stations but every time the police called him, he bribed them into dropping her case. When she was about to give up, 7 months down the road, Miss Elizabeth Kibukamusoke (Psychologist) who is the mother of Zachary Mugabi, the C.E.O of Titl /TrueSoil intervened. ‚ÄúThese kids are so young, she said. They need to be with their mother.‚Äù With the help of a few lawyers & police, Joyce finally got her children back.  Women are suffering because they don‚Äôt know where to start. Joyce says she wants young girls to know they don‚Äôt have to depend on a man because it‚Äôs so difficult to start life from zero.   It doesn‚Äôt matter how hard things may be. You don‚Äôt need to give up but be strong. You have to stand your ground. I can say I am somewhere. Why not you? You don‚Äôt need to know everything but at least have the passion to learn.‚ÄùAfter her Bootcamp, Joyce applied for a Junior Developer position at Pivot payments and she got the job. She worked for a few months & because of her passion & dedication, her boss decided to train her as a data analyst.  She was accepted into the UN Women's Training of Trainers program for ‚ÄúAfrican Girls Can Code Initiative (AGCCI).‚Äù The training took place in Dar es Salam for a week. With the training, & in addition to her Data analyst job, Joyce will use her Software skills to teach under-privileged Ugandan girls how to code.  #refactory #titl #codequeen #unwomen #unwomenuganda #unicef #savethechildren #undp #fidaug

Advocate for favorable legislation and consideration in national planning. 3. Advocate for minimum remuneration for developers. 4. Get an upper hand in government software procurement. 5. Establish a code of conduct 6. Streamline professional growth paths to increase competencies and world-wide competitiveness. 7. Arbitration in cases of professional misconduct and malpractice between members and clients. 8. Identify emerging trends, jobs and consultancy opportunities for members. 9. Identify and position members for potential investment opportunities within the software industry in Uganda and East Africa. 10. Create strong linkages in skills between industry and academia by providing world-class skills certification paths. And many other benefits. The Guild of Professional Software Engineers and IT Practitioners will comprise of the following operationalization committees: 1. Professional training and Certification Committee  2. CONVERSATION TITLE: Transform your Upstream Operations through Digital Transform
CONTENT:
Dear Atim


In a sustained period of lowered oil price demand, upstream operators are adapting to change by looking at strategies that enhance their operating margins and positively impact profitability.

 

In this context, we are seeing rapid deployment of emerging technologies and digital transformation strategies to improve visibility of critical assets, reduce operational spend, and develop production performance.

 

There are several opportunity areas where Digital Transformation can make a positive impact across Upstream Oil & Gas:

 

  • Wellhead Automation & Monitoring - Optimizing traditional instrumented wellheads where wireless monitoring is helping operators significantly reduce start-up and commissioning times.
  • Abandoned wells Monitoring - Where wireless monitoring reduces expensive and unsafe manual mobilization and monitoring practices.
  • Non-Intrusive Wellhead Erosion Monitoring - Technologies such as acoustic sand monitoring are a great way to detect sand and optimize well production.
  • Chemical Injection Skids - Automated chemical injection process and data analytics can help achieve the perfect balance in dosing to maximize upstream asset integrity, and at the same time avoid over-injection of expensive dosing chemicals. Also, the impact of the system on asset integrity can be gauged with wireless-enabled real-time corrosion monitoring. 
  • Predictive Analytics in Artificial Lift Systems - The goal is to use software-based closed-loop optimization to minimize lifting costs and maximize hydrocarbon recovery.

 

Emerson's Plantweb Digital Ecosystem has a comprehensive suite of solutions that support customers in increasing reliability by providing greater visibility, lowering costs by reducing manual processes, and enhancing production efficiency by supporting automated workflows and analytics-based optimization.


Click the link below to access our detailed webinar that covers Emerson's entire digital transformation portfolio for Upstream Oil & Gas.
